the drastic change of economic orientation from the economic policies in new independent Namibia in 1990 to the current Namibian economy, which has been transformed to a liberal market economy with policy changes, which has been fostered by the Asian Tigers and South Africa (Khama, 2009; Kukada, 1999).
95% of Namibians became accustomed to social free security services and national employment when the movement “Struggle of Liberation” from which Namibia got independence promised to provide people with all basic requirements. With independence this was not possible. Therefore, the socio-cultural organisations should promote socio-cultural environments and should implement policies for policies to provide infrastructural services with a focus on income and access to public services through their strong ties with government, which would help in re-administration in the areas that promote economic development, namely, urban economic development (Ebric, 2010; Porter, 2003; Spivak. 1995). In particular, Bezugly, Moran, and Turek recommend the adoption of policies that can facilitate employment opportunities through technical training, lower costs of specific start-ups of business, extend social protection, easier access to formation and development of cooperatives and micro-enterprises, which would provide income for the unemployed. Moreover, technical assistance would advance the modernisation of cooperatives and micro-enterprises as well as rural administration, which would, certainly, have positive impact in the reduction in poverty
